title.narrative: 1.2: QUALITY SOCIAL SERVICE PACKAGES (0-59 MONTHS)

description.narrative: 1.2: Improved, quality social service packages (for maternal and newborn health, child health, nutrition, water and sanitation, birth registration, early stimulation and development, pre-primary education, and social protection) are developed, enhanced and made available to girls and boys (0â€“59 months) and pregnant women especially, which contributes to Access To Justice, Equitable Access To Quality Education, Hiv Prevention, Immunization, Maternal And Newborn Health, Prevention Of Stunting And Other Forms Of Malnutrition, Treatment Of Severe Acute Malnutrition. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Public Engagement, Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Evaluations, Research And Data, Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Harnessing Power Of Business And Markets, Operational Support To Programme Delivery, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, United Nations Working Together. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2022, increased proportions of girls and boys (0â€“59 months) and pregnant women, especially in targeted municipalities in six deprived provinces and peri-urban Luanda, have equitable access to and use essential quality social services (for maternal and newborn health, child health, nutrition, water and sanitation, birth registration, early stimulation and development, pre-primary education and social protection)

description.narrative: Technical assistance, advocacy and capacity building efforts have contributed to strengthening of community health information systems to be integrated to national HMIS, development of models for ECD and increasing birth registration. The Todos Unidos Para a Primeira Infância (TUPPI) ECD model strengthened and reinforced nurturing care and parenting skills of 660 families in four provinces, with 1,766 children from 0-5 benefited from improved caregiving. UNICEF Angola has also contributed to continuity of essential health services, including immunization campaigns, resulting in a total of 1,519,506.000 children vaccinated against polio. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:27/08/2020
